Switzerland lies between latitudes 45° and 48° N, and longitudes 5° and 11° E. It contains three basic topographical features:

Two rivers – the Rhine in the north and the Geneva in the south – flow through eastern Switzerland at almost right-angles, forming one of the most extensive river valleys in the world;

Three high-altitude ranges – Mont Blanc, the Grand Alps and the Graubünden – are found scattered along the border of the Alpine country;

Over 200 peaks reach 2,000 meters, making it the highest country in Europe and, second in the world.

